I responded to a cold email: â€œThis isnâ€™t my priority. Best of luck with your outreach!â€

Got hit with an objection handle: â€œJust to confirm - closing more deals faster isnâ€™t a priority?â€

I get the approach: The idea is to â€œtrapâ€ the prospect into a question they canâ€™t say no to.

â€œWhat sales leader wouldnâ€™t want more deals, faster?â€

Hereâ€™s the problem: Iâ€™m not objecting to the proposed outcome. Closing more deals faster is ALWAYS a priority for me.

Iâ€™m just already working on my top priorities to help my teams close more deals faster. Weâ€™ve identified tools supporting those priorities and are in execution mode.

My objection wasnâ€™t to the outcome. It was the approach this solution takes to drive that outcome. The problems they solve to drive that outcome are not painful for me.

When you get a no, donâ€™t fall back to the high-level outcome:

- â€œOh, you donâ€™t want to save money on your HR solutions?â€

- â€œReally, you donâ€™t want to reduce the risk of getting hacked?â€

- â€œHuh, you donâ€™t want your developers to be happy and productive?â€

Of course your buyers want those outcomes. If they are objecting, they likely either:

- Donâ€™t believe you can drive that outcome

- Believe a different approach will work better

Find out which of those your objection falls under and address that for better success.

Hereâ€™s what that follow-up might look like:

â€œMakes perfect sense youâ€™ve already got a handle on this. Usually this means youâ€™ve got a similar solution in place and I didnâ€™t do a good job sharing how we are different, or you are attacking this priority through a completely different approach.

Can I ask where you fall?â€

Next time you hear â€œthis isnâ€™t a priorityâ€ to something that you know should be a priority, give this a shot!

comments.commentText: right on! the classic trap question can backfire when you're not addressing the real reason behind the objection
Gotta understand before you â€œtrapâ€

posts.content: We have been hearing a lot about working hours from some of the Industry greats from India. Last I counted we were between 70 - 90 hours per week and asked to work instead of staring at our wives on the weekend. He called it in three simple words - Quality over Quantity!
